║  Location: Bridge - Process Management Terminal                       ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  ARIA BACKUP: Critical alert, Operator!                                │
│                                                                        │
│  The life support system is being overwhelmed by rogue processes.      │
│  I've captured a snapshot of all running processes before the          │
│  monitoring system went offline.                                       │
│                                                                        │
│  Your task: Analyze the process snapshot, cross-reference with the     │
│  system logs, and identify which processes need to be terminated.      │
│                                                                        │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

MISSION BRIEFING:

The file 'ps_snapshot.txt' contains output from 'ps aux' - a list of all
running processes at the time of capture.

The file 'system_log.txt' contains warnings about which processes are
causing problems.

OBJECTIVES:

1. Examine ps_snapshot.txt to understand running processes
2. Read system_log.txt to identify problematic processes
3. Find the PIDs of the THREE rogue processes
4. Write the PIDs to 'terminate.txt' (space-separated, any order)

Example: If you identify PIDs 1234, 5678, and 9012, create:
  echo "1234 5678 9012" > terminate.txt

Then verify: ./verify

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

USEFUL COMMANDS:

  cat ps_snapshot.txt       - View all processes
  grep "pattern" file       - Search for pattern in file
  ps aux | grep name        - (For reference) How you'd search live

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

PROCESS ANATOMY (ps aux columns):
USER  PID  %CPU  %MEM  VSZ  RSS  TTY  STAT  START  TIME  COMMAND

  • PID  = Process ID (the number you need to identify)
  • %CPU = Percentage of CPU being used
  • %MEM = Percentage of memory being used
  • STAT = Process state (R=running, S=sleeping, Z=zombie)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
